fg_segments: Privacy Policy Many data analysts and data savvy managers are very interested to learn how they can analyze customer data to understand how their clients act and react.
That's why they collect data on their behaviour. Here we describe the type of data we collect on DataCamp to give you a better experience, and to build a better product.

Website Visitors Like most website operators, DataCamp collects non-personally-identifiable information of the sort that web browsers and servers typically make available, such as the browser type, language preference, referring site, and the date and time of each visitor request.
DataCamp's purpose in collecting non-personally identifiable information is to better understand how DataCamp's visitors use its website.
From time to time, DataCamp may release non-personally-identifiable information in the aggregate, e.g., by publishing a report on trends in the usage of its website.
DataCamp also collects potentially personally-identifiable information like Internet Protocol (IP) addresses.

DataCamp does not use such information to identify its visitors, however, and does not disclose such information, other than under the same circumstances that it uses and discloses personally-identifiable information, as described below.
Gathering of Personally-Identifiable Information Certain visitors to DataCamp's websites choose to interact with DataCamp in ways that require DataCamp to gather personally-identifiable information.
The amount and type of information that DataCamp gathers depends on the nature of the interaction.
In each case, DataCamp collects such information only insofar as is necessary or appropriate to fulfill the purpose of the visitor's interaction with DataCamp.
DataCamp does not disclose personally-identifiable information other than as described below.
And visitors can always refuse to supply personally-identifiable information, with the caveat that it may prevent them from engaging in certain website-related activities.
Aggregated Statistics DataCamp may collect statistics about the behavior of visitors to its websites.
For instance, DataCamp may reveal how many downloads a particular version got, or say which plugins are most popular based on checks from api.
DataCamp, a web service used by DataCamp installations to check for new versions of DataCamp and plugins.
However, DataCamp does not disclose personally-identifiable information other than as described below.ses personally-identifiable information, as described below.

Protection of Certain Personally-Identifiable Information DataCamp discloses potentially personally-identifiable and personally-identifiable information only to those of its employees, contractors, and affiliated organizations that (i) need to know that information in order to process it on DataCamp's behalf or to provide services available at DataCamp's websites, and (ii) that have agreed not to disclose it to others.
Some of those employees, contractors and affiliated organizations may be located outside of your home country; by using DataCamp's websites, you consent to the transfer of such information to them.
DataCamp will not rent or sell potentially personally-identifiable and personally-identifiable information to anyone.

Other than to its employees, contractors, and affiliated organizations, as described above, DataCamp discloses potentially personally-identifiable and personally-identifiable information only when required to do so by law, or when DataCamp believes in good faith that disclosure is reasonably necessary to protect the property or rights of DataCamp, third parties, or the public at large.

If you are a registered user of a DataCamp website and have supplied your email address, DataCamp may occasionally send you an email to tell you about new features, solicit your feedback, or just keep you up to date with what's going on with DataCamp and our products.
We primarily use our blog to communicate this type of information, so we expect to keep this type of email to a minimum.

If you send us a request (for example via a support email or via one of our feedback mechanisms), we reserve the right to publish it in order to help us clarify or respond to your request or to help us support other users.

DataCamp takes all measures reasonably necessary to protect against the unauthorized access, use, alteration, or destruction of potentially personally-identifiable and personally-identifiable information.
Cookies A cookie is a string of information that a website stores on a visitor's computer, and that the visitor's browser provides to the website each time the visitor returns.
DataCamp uses cookies to help DataCamp identify and track visitors, their usage of DataCamp website, and their website access preferences.

DataCamp visitors who do not wish to have cookies placed on their computers should set their browsers to refuse cookies before using DataCamp's websites, with the drawback that certain features of DataCamp's websites may not function properly without the aid of cookies.
Privacy Policy Changes Although most changes are likely to be minor, DataCamp may change its Privacy Policy from time to time, and in DataCamp's sole discretion.
DataCamp encourages visitors to frequently check this page for any changes to its Privacy Policy.
Your continued use of this site after any change in this Privacy Policy will constitute your acceptance of such change.

About DataCamp

Privacy Policy
Many data analysts and data savvy managers are very interested to learn how they can analyze customer data to understand how their clients act and react. That's why they collect data on their behaviour. Here we describe the type of data we collect on DataCamp to give you a better experience, and to build a better product.
Website Visitors
Like most website operators, DataCamp collects non-personally-identifiable information of the sort that web browsers and servers typically make available, such as the browser type, language preference, referring site, and the date and time of each visitor request. DataCamp’s purpose in collecting non-personally identifiable information is to better understand how DataCamp’s visitors use its website. From time to time, DataCamp may release non-personally-identifiable information in the aggregate, e.g., by publishing a report on trends in the usage of its website. DataCamp also collects potentially personally-identifiable information like Internet Protocol (IP) addresses. DataCamp does not use such information to identify its visitors, however, and does not disclose such information, other than under the same circumstances that it uses and discloses personally-identifiable information, as described below.
			
Gathering of Personally-Identifiable Information
Certain visitors to DataCamp’s websites choose to interact with DataCamp in ways that require DataCamp to gather personally-identifiable information. The amount and type of information that DataCamp gathers depends on the nature of the interaction. In each case, DataCamp collects such information only insofar as is necessary or appropriate to fulfill the purpose of the visitor’s interaction with DataCamp. DataCamp does not disclose personally-identifiable information other than as described below. And visitors can always refuse to supply personally-identifiable information, with the caveat that it may prevent them from engaging in certain website-related activities.

Some of those employees, contractors and affiliated organizations may be located outside of your home country; by using DataCamp’s websites, you consent to the transfer of such information to them. DataCamp will not rent or sell potentially personally-identifiable and personally-identifiable information to anyone. Other than to its employees, contractors, and affiliated organizations, as described above, DataCamp discloses potentially personally-identifiable and personally-identifiable information only when required to do so by law, or when DataCamp believes in good faith that disclosure is reasonably necessary to protect the property or rights of DataCamp, third parties, or the public at large. If you are a registered user of a DataCamp website and have supplied your email address, DataCamp may occasionally send you an email to tell you about new features, solicit your feedback, or just keep you up to date with what’s going on with DataCamp and our products. Cookies
A cookie is a string of information that a website stores on a visitor’s computer, and that the visitor’s browser provides to the website each time the visitor returns. DataCamp uses cookies to help DataCamp identify and track visitors, their usage of DataCamp website, and their website access preferences. DataCamp visitors who do not wish to have cookies placed on their computers should set their browsers to refuse cookies before using DataCamp’s websites, with the drawback that certain features of DataCamp’s websites may not function properly without the aid of cookies.
